name: Millinery Mother Original
description:
Original Painting on Rives BFK paper, Tan Color 

Description: 

Millinery Mother is a personal piece for a show.  Millinery Mother is the creator of all Milliner's. Milliners were typically woman hat designers in the 1800s.  The origin of the name is likely the Middle English Milener, as in an inhabitant of Milan or one who makes or deals in items from the Italian city, known for its fashion and clothing. Enjoy! 

Medium: Acrylic, gouache, ink, graphite

Unframed Size: 30x40 in

Framed with back matte: 36x48 in


Orignal Signature on right bottom corner

name: Queen of Fall Original
description:
Original Painting on Rives BFK paper, Tan Color

Description:

 This series was inspired by my interest in animals and fashion. My inspiration came from, Alexander McQueen, and J.C Leyendecker.  The title saids the whole piece, she is the mother of all queens of the fall.  Mother of the woods brings all animals life in peace with one another.   Creating the queen was by creating a very fashionable and well sophisticated woman in the woods. Enjoy!

Triptych Unframed Size: 30x40 in each

Framed with back matte: 6x3 ft 

Orignal Signature on right bottom corner

name: Church Original
description:
Original Painting on Rives BFK paper, Tan Color

Description:   
In the early 20th century, Sunday church services provided African American women who worked as domestic servants or in other subservient roles the only real chance to break away from their drab, dreary workday uniforms. They favored bright colors and textured fabric — the bolder the better and topped their outfits off with a flamboyant hat, or “crown.”  Each piece of clothing you wear means something and for hats its the same thing, each type of hat means and has a history behind it. Hope you enjoyed this piece as much as I did to create for the lovers out there for fashion!! 


Medium: Acrylic, gouache, ink, graphite and gold Leaf 

Unframed Size: 16x20 in

Framed with matte: 18x24in

 Signature on right bottom corner
